    "costs": "7500",
    "actions_taken": [
      "Shut down all operations",
      "Barricaded affected areas",
      "Performed safety stand down with all crews",
      "Retrieved basket safely",
      "Inspected all tools in basket - found in good working order",
      "Swapped out damaged P-tank",
      "Repaired damaged handrail sections",
      "Inspected all slings and lifting gear",
      "Removed damaged or degraded slings from service",
      "Revised replacement frequency of slings"
    ],
    "summary": "On March 13, 2024, during plug and abandon operations on jack-up rig Enterprise 264, a crane stinger failed while offloading a 4x40 foot basket weighing 13,000 pounds from a workboat. The stinger, rated for 9.80 tons vertical pull, parted due to internal corrosion from moisture buildup in the socket over time. The basket fell upside down onto the control room, P-tanks, and platform on top of living quarters, causing approximately $7,500 in damage. No injuries occurred. Investigation revealed that the stinger had not been specifically inspected prior to use, and inspection procedures (Preventive Maintenance Daily checklist, cold work permit, and JSA) did not explicitly require stinger inspection.",
    "recommendations": [
      "BSEE Houma District has no recommendations for the Office of Incident Investigations at this time"
    ],
    "key_phrases": [
      "stinger parted",
      "corrosion built up from moisture inside the socket over time",
      "failure to inspect the stinger",
      "Preventive Maintenance Daily checklist did not clearly identify inspecting the stinger",
      "stinger was degraded inside the crimp on the wire rope making it difficult to identify",
      "stinger was left on the crane whether in use or not"
    ]
  },
